Meanwhile in a parallel universe where the scenarists aren't bigots when trying to justify Dido's skin color:

"So Dido's backstory is that she was enslaved and was owned by a cruel roman lord who treated her poorly, killed her family, and used her for s..xual pleasure. She could barely escape and she now seeks a way to avenge her and her family. She also wants to free the other slaves owned by that evil roman lord who are her friends. Naturally, she hates romans above all, and it is her endless hatres that drives and motivates her. One day however, her prejudices are challenged when she meets a roman legionnaire that was spared so that he could betray the roman army. This roman gradually sympathizes and Dido slowly and unknowingly falls in love with him. Eventually they make out, close to when the season ends. In the very last episode however, when Dido is finally one last gladius strike away to killing the evil roman lord and be avenged, the plot twist reveals that the roman legionnaire she so much loves is actually the evil roman lord's son. Then the season 2 ends with this cliffhanger, and how Dido handles this situation will be revealed in season 3."

"Wow, what a beautiful and credible backstory! You also brought in much needed depth into the character! Can you imagine a parallel universe where we had defined Dido by only her race and gender and justified her skin color by saying that she is basically 170 years old?"

"Yeah, that would make us lazy bigots, wouldn't it? But such a stupid parallel universe couldn't possibly exist. Right? RIGHT???"
Agreed. If it claimed to be "historically based" it should be.

The funny thing is they want to be inclusive about different ethnicities while portraying Romans, a nation that did have multiple ethnicities with many reaching positions of power, as villains. I wonder if they just can't wrap their heads around the idea of an Empire not being pure evil.

The really sad part is you actually could have had a perfectly legitimate African character that made sense with a little creative writing for backstory as Rome was in conflict with Nubia in 21 B.C.E only 31 years prior to the beginning of season 2 (something like say, she was taken very young as part of a Roman slave raid), rather than 160 some years out of date. Want a real shout out to history, make her from Nubia and call her Amanirenas.

Mental gymnastics indeed. I happen to be one of THOSE people myself... who prefers the movie be atleast somewhat historically accurate if they claim its based on historical events.
If they are to make a movie about some kingdom in Africa or China or Japan etc. and all the cast is white, i would equally be like: ''What in the F is that garbage?'' That seems to not matter at all though?!
I heard the historical  advisors walked out on season 2 due to the writing team wanting to make their "ideal history" if I remember correctly

The sad truth is that in the name of representation, they swap out characters as though there were not a multitude of actual stories to choose from. This is either because they do not know this is the case (meaning they are grossly ignorant of history), or worse, that they only see legitimacy in tokenizing stories of "accepted" ethnicities (which would be actual racism).
The reality is that if we could trust them to get the story right and handle the source material correctly and with care and respect, we all would love to see stories that delve into the rich histories from around the globe. Give us a show accurately depicting the Inca... the Maori... the Inuit, the steppe peoples... the Polish/Lithuanian/Teuton conflicts... the people of Cush... there are so many peoples and places to choose from, each with intrigue, conflict, and enough action and drama to keep any male riveted (because butted mail just won't do). We live in a day and age where access to these histories has never been more accessible... And yet has never been more deliberately ignored.

The moment I sorta got fed up with the whole Dido plot was when they, through 2 entire episodes, had a big plot to try n save her from her wounds and making it seem like we should really care a lot.... only.. we were never really introduced to her. No "This is why she's important", no character building etc. I had no relation to her, meaning, to me, it was simply a character to fill up a few holes and trying too hard to make her seem important, where loads of other characters with more importance and screen time, die like flies and no body gives a shit.
As a North African, I am sad that our people are not represented very well or often in the media, I never see a proper representation of an Amazigh character :(
Hail to Metatronus Nobilius Primus! Defender of Historical Accuracy! Proud are we all to be in his Legions!

Another point in favor of historical accuracy:

The majority of the population does not learn about history from books anymore, they do it from exactly these shows and movies.
That's why there are experts on those fields in the first place, and repeating the fantasies leads to distorted views, like believing the past either being too barbaric or too modern.

And it is not just history. I have seen the excuse "It's just a show" also a lot on comments pointing out physical or scientific inaccuracies in Science Fiction or even logical ones in Hgh Fantasy.
It's all the same there, minus the '-ism' accusations as long as you don't talk about people. (They may call you a smartass, nitpicker or nerd instead)

This is basically anti-intellectualism, because people can't live outside their feel-good bubbles anymore, let alone admit mistakes or gaps in their knowledge.

No, there were no black people in Carthage. The quoted poster is right. There was very little contact between North Africa and Sub-Saharan Africa. The only way would have been through Egypt. If any woman with Black ancestry had lived in Carthage, she would have been mixed with Phoenicians to such a degree that she wouldn't have any Black African features left. People with less than 5% of a certain racial type simply don't look like this race anymore, but more like the 95% of their other ancestors.

Black Romans are another modern myth. In Latin there is not even a word for Black people. The darkest people Romans had ever met were Ethiopians, so dark-skinned people are called "Aethiopes" in Latin. Ethiopians are not 100% Black, but something in between Semitic and Black people.
The only chance that Romans would have had to make contact with real Black African would be the Nubians living in Upper Egypt and Sudan (Kush). The existence of this land was known to the Romans, but southern Egypt was never part of the Roman Empire. Rome only conquered the northern part of the Ptolemean kingdom, whose population looked more or less the same as today's population of Lower Egypt. The fact that Latin has no word for the Nubian people is another proof that Romans made no significant contact with them. The Romans had heard rumors about black-skinned people, but they were not part of the Empire. The darkest people Romans were aware of and had a word for were the Ethiopians, a rather Semitic looking people (similar to Arabs) with mostly straight, not curly hair. They were noticeably darker than Mediterranean people, but not Black Africans, as we know them. Black Romans are a myth - never happened in reality. Get this nonsense out of your heads!

1991's Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves had a far better explanation for how black Morgan Freeman's Moorish character ended up in medieval England in that he escaped from prison with Robin after the latter was captured during the crusades. No one thought anything of it as it made plenty of sense and Morgan's character really added to the cast of the movie.

But this... this strong black Carthagian woman ending up in Germania?? Now that's just corrupted writing.
There are many historically plausible ways to have black characters in a history show about Europe, but the writers always choose a dumb way to do so.

There are thousands of possible stories that either haven't been written yet, or haven't been explored, showcased, exposed to western audiences (or international ones). Why do people feel the need to revise ones which already existed from time periods that do not fit our current socio-political views?  If the writers and producers behind these disasters had any talent or creative vision, they might be able to tell a new story featuring roles which help represent people of colour, ethnic minorities, etc.

The reason why people are so reactive to this, is because the common man often looks to media, rather than anything credible, to determine their understanding of history.

It should be required to have a minute-long disclaimer before any "historically based" media, noting that it's a work of historical fiction, unless specified otherwise. 

This would at least warn people not to accept 300 (based off a graphic novel), Barbarians, Woman King, Gladiator, Apocalypto, Vikings etc. as immediate fact!  Trust me, people blindly follow movies to a T, and it shows; been dealing with Vikings for an age now.

Granted, you likely won't ever have anything that's 100% historical, but at least make it within the ball park.  Make it cohesive.
I'd love to see you make a video about what God of War: Ragnar√∂k gets right and (more importantly) wrong about the many aspects Norse gods and culture.
Spot on observation.  It's like Germanicus being called Germanicus before he was Germanicus.  I also have a problem with "historical" shows where Vikings don't wear helmets.
So long as history is blighted by falsehood, Metatron will fight it!

I think this is the best video I've seen so far talking about this. I like how you defend historical accuracy while also pointing out that there absolutely were black people in Carthage and the Roman Empire. They were a minority but they were there.

One thing I would have specifically pointed out is the long-established trans-Saharan trade routes which Carthage was involved in. People treat the Sahara as if it's an impassable barrier but it isn't, and it wasn't then. There have always been peoples living in the Sahara, who moved from well to well, knew where to find water and food, were accustomed to the hard way of life there. These people passed back and forth, north and south in the Sahara trading goods between the peoples north and south of the desert. Carthage famously imported ivory, gold and such goods from sub-Saharan Africa. Some of this would then be exported from Carthage out into the Mediterranean world. In turn the Carthaginians also exported their own products to sub-Saharan Africa.

So, people and goods moved back and forth. Black people from south of the Sahara would have come north as traders, guards for caravans, mercenaries looking for work in Carthage's wars, slaves. Some slaves would later be freed and become free Carthaginian citizens who could have any kind of profession.

By extension, some black people, once in Carthage, were entirely capable of traveling to other parts of the Mediterranean world. Some of them involuntarily as slaves, others voluntarily as merchants or soldiers or what have you.

I would also say it's definitely not impossible for a black person to have ended up in Germania, but EXTREMELY unlikely for one to end up on the Germanic side, and far more likely for one on the Roman side. Once in the Roman Empire, a free black person could travel anywhere from Palestine to Spain, from Greece to Gaul. An enslaved black person, or a black freedman/freedwoman in the retinue of a Roman patron (freed slaves became clients to former masters), or simply a freeborn black person who was employed by a rich Roman, would go with that Roman if, say, he was a senator who was assigned a post somewhere like Roman-controlled Germania on the west bank of the Rhine. Roman soldiers and officers from more upper-class backgrounds were also known to bring a slave or freedman along to attend them on campaign, so you might actually see a few black people among the camp followers that trailed along with the legions. And a free black person could even sign up to become a legionary himself. Otherwise there was the auxilia, in which non-Roman subject peoples within the empire (or from client kingdoms just outside it) would serve alongside the legions. You would find some black people among them in the North African auxilia units. So in such a scenario, yes, a time-travelling observer in Germania during the time period this show is set might well observe some black people among the legions. But not among the Germanic tribes.

By the way, the reason I mention slaves/freedmen so much isn't because black people were particularly likely to be slaves back then (racialized slavery came later; in the Roman world, people of any color could be slaves), but more because slaves were one of the main categories of long-distance travelers in the ancient Mediterranean world. Slave traders would take them from place to place, by land or ship, from market to market, one trader buying from another, until the enslaved person was purchased at a market. Many black people in the Roman world would have been freeborn, but many others would have been slaves or freedmen.

On another note, it's documented that the Garamantes, a North African people who lived in what's now Libya, that was known for their role in the slave trade, would raid south of the Sahara as far as Lake Chad (where the population was incontrovertibly black) and take their captives back up to the North African coast. Some of the captives would be kept as slaves on the Garamantes' own farms, others would be sold on to slave traders from Rome, Greece, Carthage, Egypt or whomever else would buy. And then, again, once in Rome, a slave might be freed one day (depending on various circumstances) and become a free citizen.

So the idea of a black person in Roman-era Europe is far from implausible. But the Dido character specifically is ludicrously implausible for many other reasons.
Historically accuracy is crucial for education. So please do keep up the good work.

I feel bad for North Africans and the descendants of the Phoenician people. Their peoples history is very misrepresented and unfairly attributed to black Africans rather than their own people all in the name of inclusivity and equality. From Hannibal of Carthage to made up fictional characters representing them in cinema, even though there is clear historical account and statues made in their image. I‚Äôve seen plenty of data that Phoenician people have the closest DNA relating to the same ethnic groups in the Near East as in ancient times. Which would of course make all the sense in the world. Those people are in fact the Lebanese people. These Mediterranean people do not appear to me to be black Africans. I‚Äôm very puzzled why the ‚ÄúHistory Channel‚Äù would depict one of their people as black in their TV show if it‚Äôs about the truth and historical accuracy for educational purposes. Them having a black population shouldn‚Äôt give them the right to rewrite history. It‚Äôs like us all knowing all presidents in America were white men but later in history a film maker and TV show creates George Washington as a black woman because America had 1 black president or a black population. It‚Äôs ridiculous and unfair to the historical facts.

Many seem to forget that the Chuddle Dollops were Duck's property, he bought them.

Think of it this way;
Yellow guy owns a pair of batteries in his chest,
Duck bought a pack of Chuddle Dollops.

Remember that just because a character uses the item doesn't mean they're tied to it.

Yellow guy uses the shovel to dig up Duck(who dies again later on by Stain Edwards the Forever boy)
Duck handles the batteries in order to set everything "right"
Red guy opens the Chuddle Dollops

1:23  I think it was the father who killed David.  That is why you hear her tell her son to look before crossing (which she wouldn't say if she was driving).  It would explain why the father is always silent and seen as a hidden threat, as he was the one who (maybe unintentionally) killed the family (like he does with the donor family... heh heh.. _donner_ family).

I think Red Guy and Duck are Super Ego (awareness of the bigger picture) and Id (baser instinct) respectively, which is why Yellow Guy David sees only them in the higher rooms: they are parts of his mind.

Maybe it could explain the themes of the episodes too.  In the first series, the first episode is about creativity.  Maybe it was David's imagination that brought him from the void of death.  Then you have time and love, a subconscious awareness of mortality and knowing something is missing (his parents' love and the ritual of his funeral).  The computer episode could be him trying to seek out more information to his well being, with health and dreams again referring to subconsciously knowing he is rotting in a grave and having a neverending nightmare due to being dead but not knowing it.

Even the 2nd season deals with issues relating to purpose (jobs), an attempt to understand his fate, escape (to see the boundaries of his spiritual prison) and enlightenment.  Leslie may be a mix of what David remembers of his mother and how he might view his own body (being stitched back together after getting hit face first by a car).  It is not his mother on the (second to) top floor.. it is still part of David's Limbo prison.  Even the bit at the end with him becoming "stupid" may be David refusing to accept that he is dead, and he would rather be blithely ignorant than come to terms with his mortality.

The entire story may be akin to *The Others (2001)* from Alejandro Amenabar.

Goggins is funny without trying because he is so real it‚Äôs comedic and refreshing

I appreciate the fact that he takes life seriously. As I‚Äôm fighting cancer right now I know‚Äîevery moment counts. And you have nothing without your health. Absolutely nothing. And so many diseases and mental afflictions are preventable with dedication and living life with intention. 

That being said‚Äîthis particular message and mentality (no rest, no play, no vacation) is just as pathologically American and unhealthy. 

The ability to shift gears between motivation, forward center of mass, drive and reprieve, solitude, embracing the sensations of being present in the outdoors and enjoying the gifted consciousness that we have as human beings (when we could have been bacteria, a rodent, a cow, a tree) is ALSO a skill worth developing.

Balance is key. And when you‚Äôre in a position like mine‚Äîwhich you all will be at some point. You will remember those solitary moments‚Äîthe accomplishments, yes‚Äîbut also the quality of your relationships, and the quality of your moments. All of them.

Motivation is present just for a brief time, mostly when you start something and you are so happy that you started, because you are thinking of the results you will achieve in the end. But then, in the following days, when it becomes a routine, motivation is the first thing that abandons you, and you stand there all alone and disappointed, thinking "do I even want this anymore?". That's why discipline beats everything else, if you don't depend yourself on discipline, you'll never finish anything.

I love Goggins because of that. He's truthful and he follows through with his own advice. He's flawed, and he's open about it. His vulnerability coupled with his mental perseverance makes him an extraordinary human. He turned physical effort into a mental one, and that completely changes the situation.
Starting to think that way helped me tremendously, and many others.
Goggin‚Äôs tenacity is contagious.

David Goggins, you have discovered the secret of the great yogis of India without knowing (or maybe you do).  That facing suffering without fear of suffering leads to the overcoming of suffering until it eventually bends to your will.  You are an amazing human being.  Thank you for your strength.

My subscription box company Two Witches Whimsy is including this amazing Juniper Hazelnut Chocolate Cookie recipe this month! It's SUPER unique! I'll share it here:
-2 tsp whole juniper berries            
-8oz unsalted butter, softened          
-1 cup packed brown sugar 
-¬Ω tsp salt                                          
-2 tsp vanilla extract                            
-1¬æ cups flour
-¬æ cup Dutch cocoa powder            
-6oz toasted hazelnuts                        
-¬æ cup milk chocolate     
-1 cup raw sugar (optional)
Place the juniper berries in a dry pan over medium heat and dry roast for a few minutes. When you start to smell the berries, take them off the heat and let cool. Place the cooled juniper berries in a spice grinder or mortar and pestle and grind them. The result will be slightly wet and sticky. 
Add butter, brown sugar, salt, vanilla and juniper berry paste to a large bowl or mixer bowl. With a hand mixer or stand mixer (with a paddle attachment), mix until the butter and sugar are well mixed and creamy - DO NOT beat the butter and sugar until light and fluffy.
Add the sifted flour and sifted cocoa powder, folding to incorporate. Then add the hazelnuts and milk chocolate chunks and mix. Divide the dough in half. Form a 2-2 ¬Ω inch diameter cookie dough log with each of the dough portions. Wrap each log in plastic wrap (knotting the ends tightly).
Refrigerate until the cookie dough is firm (1-2 hours or overnight).
To bake, line two cookie sheets with parchment paper. Sprinkle the raw sugar on a flat plate, then unwrap one of the cookie dough logs and roll the log in the raw sugar. Using a sharp knife, cut off the tapered end of the cookie dough log.
Then cut ‚Öì inch thick slices. Please note that because of the nuts and chocolate chips, you 
may not get clean slices, so reshape the cookies into rounds when they don‚Äôt cut cleanly. Roll the edges in the raw sugar again if you need to.
Place the cookies on the lined baking sheet. Each log should make about 10 -12 cookies. Cover the lined baking sheet with plastic wrap/parchment paper/or another baking tray and chill in the refrigerator for 30 minute before baking. This chilling is important to allow the cookies to keep their shape while baking.
While the cookies are chilling, preheat the oven to 325¬∞F. Bake in the preheated oven for 12-15 minutes. The cookie edges will be slightly firm and the middle will be soft but they will firm up as they cool. When the cookies have cooled down, remove them from the baking tray and place them on a wire rack.
The cookies will be crunchy on the outside and fudgy in the middle, and go great with hot cocoa!

*Note: You can also roll out the dough and use festive cookie cutters. If you choose to do this, roll out the dough to the desired thickness before refrigerating.

Once you have worked for yourself it is difficult to work for someone else. The mentality of the other workers is very different from yours. I would suggest you read Imagination by Neville Goddard. I went through exactly the same situation and went to a therapist. I quickly realized I was an emotionally healthy person (as I suspect you are too) living in a world with a lot of crazy people!!!! You are a beautiful soul and the business world does not support that. I had to deal with that my whole life I am 76 without loosing my soul. I learned as a young person at that time it was to escape the harsh reality of life, to visualize the exact world I wanted to live in right before I fell asleep. The key is to get excited and feel the joy of manifesting it! Learn to FEEL the joy, the wonder, the excitement of living the life you want. Put in as much detail as you can, the location, the home, the relationship(Not the person but their characteristics). Your own business and how successful, the shop, the beautify of it, your clients and how wonderful they are, that you are always making more money than you could ever possibly spend, and anything else you want in your life. When you fall asleep your subconscious works on the fastest and easiest way to create it. Sometimes it may seem it gets worse before better but that is part of the process. I have manifested travel around the world, a fur coat, the cars of my dreams. I have lived in 28 places because every time I thought I would like to live there within months I was there. I have had beautiful furnishings and great friends. The home I live in and the car I drive I visualized them exactly as they are before I fell asleep. Both were given to me!!!!! So please you don‚Äôt have mental issues you are a very creative person living in a crazy world that is harsh on the creative types. Please read Neville and Please visualize the wonderful life you can and will create before you go to sleep. I also take naps so I can visualize more!!!!! We all love you and recognize how special you are! Keep moving forward and take very good care of yourself!!!!!!

Seasons greetings beautiful Marie. Your world 
is so real to me. Having had chronic anxiety & chronic depression for years. Having been through 54 counselors, 9 psychologists & 10 psychiatrists. That was my world for over 20 years.
I was a survivor of rape throughout my life.
Deep down in my soul, I knew that I'd heal myself naturally. I did, without any antidepressants. The last predator was locked up, & eventually jailed. He was my sisters partners son. He also raped my niece who was 10 at that time. His half sister. At that stage I was oblivious to everything, being traumatized after the event, & past episodes.
I attribute my healing to having wonderful supportive daughters, loving caring parents & my grandchildren, & unconditional faith, however hard it got. My mates, my cousins, extended nieces & nephews, were brilliant. 
I recieved more support from them far more than my own siblings. Because I took the case through to court & the justice system, until he was convicted, people started off loading their sexual abuse stories to me. In order to start my healing I had to go through all of their stories & help heal them first. I was also suicidal 7 times. A lot of people wouldn't admit that, but I've always kept things blatantly real. This helps you in so many ways. A lot of people really don't know how to take your honesty. Now my whole life is so different Marie. I'm stronger, wiser, have a beautiful totally blessed life, with so many people who love me, it's magical. 
I know you can do it too.
Like you, I'm also a florist. I love being outside in my garden & nature. I also do yoga, meditate, do Tai chi, kick box, & don't give stuff what people think about me.üòÅThat's important too. You do you, it's your life not someone elses.
You are the one who makes the ultimate decisions for you. You can do it Marie. Surround yourself with supportive loving people, like the Lalanders, your family & close friends. Do things you love to do, & slowly your life will change.
Much love & light beautiful Marie...one other thing I do.üòÅ

BOY DOES THIS TAKE ME BACK.

I had all my Pok√©mon stuff taken away in middle school (just before Gold and Silver came out stateside) because my grades were constantly so terrible. Joke's on my parents though: I actually had ADHD and I immediately found something else to fixate on.

One thing I love about pokemon, and something I feel like drives these evalgelical types away is that it fosters a lot of empathy towards creatures that are considered frightening or othered. No matter what a pokemon looks like, whether it be cute and fluffy like a mareep or more insect-like and bizzare like an araquanid, they're all seen as being capable of being appreciated and loved by people, and the player is ENCOURAGED to do so by the games mechanics straight up making high friendship with your team incredibly overpowered. You can see how an insular group who's pathologically afraid of anything "impure" or "unholy" would have no time for a franchise that's built on the principal of beauty and worth being utterly subjective and not prescribed by an authority. Like, my adoration of creatures like snakes, spiders and bats was first encouraged by pokemon forcing me to look at those sorts of creatues and seeing a potential friend and not something to be reviled and shunned.

TLDR; Pokemon is thematically centered around empathy for "the other" and evangalism fundamentally cannot have true empathy for anything not "pure".

Yeah, my entire childhood revolved around butting heads with these types in some form or another. Pokemon as a craze was my first real forray into dealing with the lunatic strain of  evangelicals, though, and middle school aged me, fresh off the release of Red and Blue, just was not prepared to deal with that. It completely and totally ruined my relationship with half of my family for over a decade, which became FAR worse in my highschool years when I discovered Dungeons and Dragons around the time when 3.5 was really getting big. 

That being said, I am not at all ashamed to admit that to this day, I have a DEEP distrust for these people, and I'll never let my guard down around them. When I was in highschool, my friend group formed an after school get together group where we took advantage of an empty classroom to play our D&D after school once a week. One of the parents found out about it, and not only did they take it to the school district to break it up on the grounds of being 'satan worship', they literally beat their own son so badly that he came to school the next week with half of his face swollen black and blue, badly screwed up ribs, and was totally banned from associating with any of us. Of course, the school was told that he had simply 'been in an accident' and it was left at that, but we all knew the truth, and it was confirmed to us a couple years later when we were all old enough to tell our parents to fuck off legally if we wanted.

From my experience where I grew up, this wasn't really even that rare among those people. I've several other examples of seeing this kind of behavior first hand, and have heard many stories of it second hand, and I don't even live in the bible belt, I live in fucking Michigan. 

The silver lining for me personally is that my mom simply didn't care, and my father was both never home and a catholic, so I didn't have to deal with that madness directly. Now, as an adult, I keep these people at a distance from my persona life, and they're a big part of the reason I live in an armed household.

I have a relevant story as someone who grew up in a deeply Christian environment during this time!

I was in first grade when Pokemon came out. Naturally, me and all of my friends started playing. My parents were a bit skeptical of it, due to how invested me and my friends had gotten with it. The fact that I could tell what Pokemon came out by its sound, or that I could tell my friends how to fight a Pokemon just by hearing them talk over the phone about it, these things were a bit weird to my parents, but they didn't stop me from playing it (surprisingly I think).

The big change happened in second grade. I went to a Christian school at the time, so anything that affected one person religiously affected us all in some way. Someone at the school got a chain letter email. Email was still new and chain letters were constantly circulating and the religious crowd was especially susceptible. All it took was one pastor taking the bait and forwarding it to his church email list and, since it came from The Pastor, it wouldn't be questioned much, and never openly. When it reached my school, it was already pastor-approved and had the same effect as it would on a church.

The letter told a story. A group of missionaries had gone to Africa to witness to an unnamed "tribe" and brought a bunch of toys with them for the kids. The toys were just generally basic shit that kids were playing with in America, and apparently Pokemon cards as well. I'm 99% sure it was definitely the cards, not toys or plushies, but the cards. You know, those things that your supposedly non-English speaking children wouldn't be able to fucking read? But hey, missionaries are dumb so... Anyway, when the kids got the cards, the people in the village started freaking out. They were identifying the pokemon as the demons from their pre-Christian religion. The letter urged parents to keep Pokemon away from their kids because Pokemon were demons, and a surprising number of parents at the school did.

My mom let me decide on my own. She figured it was only a game and even though she had some misgivings, I don't think she fully bought the story in the letter and figured there's nothing wrong as long as it stays fantasy and I'm not acting weird with it. My best friend, however, ended up fully rejecting Pokemon. Because of him, I also rejected Pokemon. My mom was proud of me for rejecting Pokemon as "evil" just on the principle that I was rejecting "evil." Tbh, I could absolutely believe the story about the kid smashing his game with a hammer (though it was definitely embellished). That shit happens in hyper-religious environments.

I didn't play Pokemon again until Soul Silver had already been out for a while. Missed out on a lot of fun times, but I've made up for it and gone back to all of the Pokemon I missed out on.

I know this topic looks and is very funny in hindsight, but I actually have a pretty painful history with it. When I was six years old I went to a Christian "private school" in Florida while all of this was going on. I say "private school" in quotes because it was just a glorified daycare center the church my dad worked at ran that taught preschool through the first grade... It was not a good start to my educational career. Anyway, I was a kid who loved Pokemon in an environment surrounded by adults who all thought Pokemon was demonic. Let's just say the result of that was the single worst, and possibly most traumatizing year of my life, the effects of which followed me well into adulthood and more or less set me up to struggle with school for the rest of my time in it. Like, the adults were laughing when they heard their kids tried to poison me and that I was regularly crying during school. To my parents credit, they never made me stop playing Pokemon despite all the hate they got for it and they did eventually pull me out of the school and send me back to public schools despite being dead set against public schools at the time. I guess adults encouraging their kids to treat their son like a monster was less appealing than me being taught about evolution; who'd of thunk? It's nice to be able to look back now and laugh at how crazy this whole thing was when at the time it did me a lot of very real damage that I'm honestly not sure I'm ever gonna be able to completely work through. So seriously, thanks for this. It's genuinely a helpful look back for me. üòä

At 11:24, the text on the page mentions that Digimon is a counterpart for an even younger audience and I absolutely need to speak up about this as a Digimon fan. For one thing, Digimon is really not a counterpart to Pokemon in anything but the most surface level- They're both multimedia franchises involving monsters that evolve, and that is the end of their similarities. But the bigger thing is claiming that it's for a younger audience is just... Demonstrably untrue. The Digimon games being released at the time, the Digimon World games, were getting T ratings by the ESRB. Its anime was pretty kid-friendly, but it went places Pokemon never dared to- There were major character deaths in Digimon that the English dub rarely censored. This book probably came out before the third season of Digimon did, but said season has a girl's Digimon partner die, causing her to go into such a deep depression that an eldritch abomination looking to understand humanity comes to the conclusion that all humans just want to have their existence deleted to eliminate their own suffering. I don't like comparing the two franchises to each other because as I said, they're not related in any meaningful way. But if we were to compare them, Digimon is the edgy one that pushes boundaries, not Pokemon.

I think it‚Äôs incredibly interesting that we‚Äôve slowing started to adopt a lower standard of filmmaking as the new normal. Like this show might very well be quite good. And the cast looks amazing. So why am I not blown away by atmosphere and tension? Because they‚Äôre forgetting how to do that. The games were incredibly atmospheric with a real sense of the world. Now, much like with The Rings Of Power, we have a premium high end TV show that looks like the a mid budget network show with commercials. And that‚Äôs what they want us to pay 15 bucks a months for. And I wanna make it clear that it‚Äôs not just the studios/streamers. This is just as much the filmmakers fault for not trying anymore. Beautifully crafted stories through motion are still possible, you just have to be able to see why it‚Äôs important to put in the work.

Some of the issues your wife had with the 2015 Escalade could have been solved by simply reviewing the owners manual.  For example, there are controls for the radio on the steering wheel, so there is no need to touch the screen to adjust volume.  Plus, there is no need to go into the screen to adjust the temperature, as you can just use the touch controls.  Plus, the way you were using the touch controls was not the right way, by repeatedly tapping/stabbing at them.  Instead, you are supposed to touch them, and glide your finger in a left to right, or right to left motion (to adjust the volume, for example).  I don't dispute that CUE takes some getting used to.  It can be a little fiddly at times.  The controls in the GMC Yukon are big and simple and easy to use, but a lot of the criticisms that Cadillac's CUE receives are unwarranted.  I find the CUE system works quite well for me, and I like it just fine.  Its also curious your wife found the HUD in the Escalade a distraction, as the HUD in the Yukon is basically exactly the same.  Some of the specific issues she was having can be attributed to this particular Escalade, which obviously was poorly maintained by the previous owner(s).  I would have hoped you would have fixed the issue with the driver seat (and hence the related issue with the overall assistance system) prior to giving the vehicle to her.

It was great to get your wife‚Äôs point of view as to how things work (or don‚Äôt) in a day to day basis.
My big take away was stay away from GM trucks when they are older.  As you went in and in about what doesn‚Äôt work, all I saw was dollar signs to fix everything.

G'day John. This is some back of the envelope food for thought based on your 40 truck business example. Applying the same rough thought process I went through while modernising the fit out of one of our older datacentre sites, this changeover from diesel to electric seems incredibly painful from an infrastructure perspective. Don't discount the eyewatering cost and physical size of infra and switchgear for MW scale power grid ties. So, the fleet is off the road if the grid is down? You think to yourself: "that's bad". Next you look at multiple grid providers or multiple ties to separate segments of the same provider's grid. Easy. You come to the realisation that you're probably going to need transformers too. More space. So, what if all your supplies are down? I guess you could eat up most of a modest sized truck marshalling yard with a handful of multi MW capable backup gensets that run on, you guessed it, diesel. Amazing, we've come full circle.

You're missing a key advantage to fuel vs battery.  The ICE fuel carriage burden effectively is only half of its nominal weight.  Why?  It all goes out the tailpipe on the trip, and on average the dead load is only half the mass you started with.  A pound of battery, on the other hand, is twice the effective weight of a pound of diesel, because you carry it every mile of every trip.

Speaking with my eldest lad today, who drives road trains carrying fuel (ie dangerous goods), there‚Äôs a point you did overlook in favour of the internal combustion engines trucks versus electric trucks.
The fuel tanks on the internal combustion engines truck typically will be around 1200 litres, let‚Äôs call it 1.2 tonnes near enough.
The further you travel and the more diesel you consume, your GVM decreases as you burn that fuel. You could ostensibly be 1.2 tonnes less GVM when you arrive at your destination, purely by the reduction in liquid fuel in your fuel tank. So the further you go and the lighter your fuel tank weight, as you consume the fuel, the more fuel efficient you become.in transport cost per tonne of payload delivered.

This doesn‚Äôt occur with the weight of the electric battery. It weighs essentially the same at the start of the trip as it does at the end of the trip, the released / consumed electrons essentially don‚Äôt reduce the weight of the battery appreciably.
So your ALWAYS paying to shift that battery from point A to point B.
There‚Äôs no efficiency gain as you progress on your trip the way that there is in a semi with its diesel tank as the fuel is consumed.
OK - 1.2 tonnes reduced to Zero tonnes of fuel when the tank is empty at your destination.
So it averages say 0.6 tonnes on average over the whole trip times every delivery the truck ever does in its entire life time of millions of kilometres.
It‚Äôs a huge amount when you factor this in to the profitability of the truck over its service life.
Truck fleet owners are already analysing the costs & potential savings of Teslas new electric trucks - the world over to try & figure out if they can be more cost competitive than their competitors in terms of their new truck capital acquisition costs, & as you‚Äôve already pointed out, the numbers just don‚Äôt add up for electric trucks.
This same point is also valid over the lifetime of electric vehicles as well - it‚Äôs not just trucks.
Thought you might find this aspect at least interesting. üëç

I saw your presentation for the first time today (Dec. 19).  Interesting and entertaining.  Watched about the first 7 minutes.  Something I thank you should make clear so you won't mislead your viewers.  This is about the zero to twenty second time and the power required.  The total efficiency of the system is included in the time.  That includes loss in the conversion from battery through motor, transmission, and power to the wheels.  Given that your calculation for power is correct, you state a requirement of about 750 kW.  you then state a ridiculously large requirement for battery size to fulfill that requirement.  There is an important point left unsaid:  The kW statement implies the energy , not the power.  This in not an unusual mistake, because many people don't know the difference between energy and power.  Power is the product of energy and time.  When you stated 750 kW you should have said kWh, or kilowatt hour.  The 20 second POWER is only 20 seconds divided by  3600 seconds   times your 750 kW, or just over 4 kWh from the battery over that 20 second interval.  Given a 100 kWh battery and neglecting any battery charging for regenerative braking, etc.,  this would allow for about 25 of the zero to sixty "runs".

- Truck drivers in AU aren't supposed to do 800km in one go regardless due to COR rules and regulations in a country.

- maintenance cost is likely to be on par with diesel but will have to spend more on tyres as truck is still heavier on a road compared to diesel, this is likely to be compensated by difference in diesel vs electricity costs

My mother had a soft top Jimny until fairly recently. It suffered from the notorious Jimny ‚Äúdeath wobble‚Äù at around 45mph. Her partner did some research into it and discovered that the soft top versions, unlike the hard tops, were built in Spain, not Japan. They supposedly produced them with greater tolerances, hence the reason for the play in the steering.

I think a lot of the Japan vs Europe reliability points come from the Japanese market.  There they treat cars (and even homes for that matter) more like appliances.  The equivalent of the MOT is far stricter, so many cars are sent abroad after only a handful of years.  So cars that don't make it to 5-10 years without a major mechanical problem would be a big issue for the manufactures, but one that rots away in 20 when it's sitting in a different country not so much.  Can't help but feel that will apply at least a bit to global operations as well.  And as all cars need to be cost-cut to some extent can you blame them for prioritising the poor sod who paid full whack to your own coffers over a theoretical owner 15 years from now?

Yep- I traded my GT4 to a dealer for a 911 T allocation. Why? The GT4 is a true track car - noisy to the point where I started wearing earplugs and too hard to get into and too small inside besides. I am 6‚Äô1‚Äù and 250 lbs - so there is that. But it is not a 911. In a 911 I can slide the seat back to where my feet don‚Äôt touch the pedals. In a 911 the dashboard is far away from you and the cabin is very inviting. The electronics are all state of the art- standard lab for example/ and a huge screen but the gt4 is old seven years ago design. And the gt4 rides hard all the time. While the 911 in comfort mode is just that comfortable- but in sport and at over 4,000 rpm it is a screaming race car. The gt4 is always harsh and hard - always. 

And this new T is fun to drive with a manual with downshift matching capability. So sort of like an automatic. 

And by the way the base engine is superb. It has smaller turbo blades than say the S or GTS - so the base engine spins up instantly - no taking a deep breath like the s or GTS does when you plant your foot down on the pedal on your he freeway or hitting a straight on a mountain road. 

The sport mode with this base engine makes fantastic back fire and popping noises when down shifting which get louder over time as the engine breaks in. A fantastic sound but the darn GT4 just howls but no pops and bangs etc- ever. The engine in the gt4 just kind of drones away - not pleasant to my ears.

The GT4 is designed to be driven for short periods of time on a track - but is too expensive and too pretty to chip and ding on a track. The T is designed to drive on a twisty country road or a mountain road which is where all us Porsche guys really drive our cars with our local porsche club.

And it is the ‚Äúreal ‚Äú Porsche - a 911 not a baby Porsche like the cayman. 

I do also own a 718 Boxster GTS and that is more fun to drive than the GT4. So trading the GT4 was easy emotionally - and I also get a new car.

I bought my 1995 in 1997 from a Chevy dealer.  It was winter, and the price was $21k.  It had 22k miles and was still under warranty.  It had every option except TPMS and ZR1, including the Z07 Autocross suspension.  It has been a very reliable, fun car.  However, the Optispark has been the bane of my existence.  Nearly every aftermarket opti has the tone ring spaced incorrectly, where it scrapes the optical sensor.  This will make it have a very short life.  So you need to disassemble any new opti, check and correct the tone ring spacing, and then reassemble it before you can use it.  The only part that dies is the optical sensor.  It takes a ridiculous amount of labor to get the opti out, mostly because of the Corvette's layout.  The 2-piece balancer helps, but everything is squished in there.  The plug wires are the most fun - be sure to label them before removing them from the old opti.

Mitch, from 1985-1993 I professionally detailed cars. I really enjoy your brilliant work. We did not have the great cleaners and equipment like you do. We used shop vacs for sweeping and extraction, garden hoses with your typical garden spray attachments, and cheap cleaners. I won't mention brands and names out of respect to those companies. I worked in Florida for a while. The sand in the carpets/seats as well as black or darker colored cars were the bane of our existence. On tough stains, crayons, markers we used Acrosol (<---spelling?) it was harsh and we learned early on to be very careful with it on fabrics, plastics, etc. Your suggestion about being careful when cleaning out stuff/personal items is so true. Along those lines, the worst cut I ever had was washing under the wheel wells with the old style wash mitts. I sliced myself wide open and back then we shoved our hands into denatured soap (ouch!) then duct taped our hands and kept going.  Not recommended! LOL! As far as black or darker cars...there was a product that was designed for those paint colors. It was a challenge not to leave swirls behind. We used electric buffers. There was some trial error finding the right speed, pads, compounds, polishes, etc. It was one of the most rewarding jobs I have ever had to date. I enjoyed peoples reactions to our hard work. God Bless you!

Having worked in a college environment, I've seen dorm rooms and faculty offices that are every bit as bad as this, and some even worse. What often tends to be the case is that the person is in mental crisis, and has reached a point where they are simply too overwhelmed to improve the situation themselves. They can't face what seems to be such an impossible task. Regarding the snow handling - some close ups show that the worn CC2 still grabs quite a bit of snow and the area of the tire covered with snow is greater than on the Tomket. So it's the snow gripping to snow, hence better handling (that also proves that CC2 thread design is really awesome) :) If the tire would we warm, straight from the garage on the snowy road, it'd probably skid until it would cool down enough. While cooling, it could cover itself with lots of snow, like a ski with no wax on, when taken from a warm room and put on the snow.
My concern would be more in city snow-salt-sand-mud pulp, where little thread would struggle to push this crap out, as the throughput of these thread 'channels' would be significantly lower. Great test, good to know etc. However, I'd still stick to 3-4 mm before the winter for CC2 and then maybe still use it in the summer and get new ones before the next winter, for such conditions, where CC2 is great (mild, mid-European winters with occasional snow and terrible 'love' of the road maintainence  teams to use salt for no good reason on each and every small street in the city... Salt ruins everything (from cars, through clothes to environment, also creating a troublesome waste category) and does not increase road safety at all. Quite the opposite actually, as it makes people drive faster than they would on the compacted snow.
Oh, BTW - yes, I agree that dry grip improves with wear. But (there's always a but ;)) we need to keep againg in mind. 20 y.o. tire may not give us such great grip anymore ;) Yet within 5-8 years I do agree. I had Sportmaxx RT, not used much, after 8 years they were still amazing in the dry, however the thread compound was significantly less elastic than before and in the wet it wasn't the same tire anymore. I've noticed that any sand on the edge of the road was also a bigger challenge compared to the same tire a year earlier, with pretty much the same thread depth (really not used much - it had almost 6 mm when I left them for recycling, after 8 seasons). I had the same observations with bicycle tires. With age they still grip in the try, but any surface imperfections, sand and dust on the road becomes more challenging. Wet becomes a disaster. As with car tyres :)

One very important thing wasn't in this test is rubber detoriation. As the car stays outside, tires gets sunlight, go between high and cold temperatures, become wet and dry and so become harder and brittle. Hardened rubber loses it's traction noticeably. That michelin tire must have done that 4000 miles in a controlled specific setup, because the rubber looks like new, soft and plush, still have the hairs on it's side. So that's not really a worn out tire. Thus I say this test doesn't reflect the real life experience much.

Also,  to see if there is fuel preasure from the tank to the fuel rail,  you simply take the plastic dust cover off the shrader valve located on the fuel rail and depress the pin,  if fuel sprays out this means your fuel pump is working and you have fuel being delivered to the engine,  if no fuel sprays out this means your fuel pump isn't working,

On the mondeo,  the imobilizer shuts power to the fuel pump in the tank and stops the starter motor from spinning,  the fact the starter motor is spinning tells me your imobilizer has deactived and permission to start has been granted by the ecu

Do you know what I do before flattening an endless sucession of batteries? I check for a spark and that fuel is actually being delivered to the carburetor or injection system. Pulling the fuel hose  in the engine bay and testing for fuel delivery allows you to flush the most degraded fuel out at the very least. Checking for fuel before and after any filter is a good idea. 

A fuel injected car will prime the fuel system for 30 seconds or so, so you can check for pump operation without ever having to crank. My Mondeo would occasionally fail to prime and require the ignition to be turned off for several minutes to reset. 

Once you are sure you're getting fuel through, an effective trick for stale fuel is to remove the plugs and get them good an hot, so hot you need gloves to put them back in. I've started cars with decade old fuel that way.

Ok one quick story about me, When I was 9 I used to go out with my friends and didn‚Äôt care about the signs. There was a car on my right hand side and I tripped on a rock so I couldn‚Äôt stand up in time. The car was coming at 40mph and I crawled and the wheel on the car broke my leg and I screamed in agony. I had my leg broken for 4 years and I‚Äôm on crutches and I hate it still, but I‚Äôm glad I‚Äôm still alive.

Another thing people don't think about is how big reaction times change between the two speeds, this advert shows what happens if you hit someone AT 30mph. 

At 30mph, if someone steps out 15 metres in front of you, you'll be braking for the last 6 metres. It takes 14 metres to stop from 30, so it's safe to say you'll be closer to 20mph by the time you hit the person that stepped out. The survival rate at 20mph is 97% or so. 

If you were doing 40mph, you'd be on the brakes for half that time. According to the RAC, 40-30mph takes around 10 metres itself, so in 3 metres you won't even be below 35mph. If you hit that same person at 35, the survival rate is only about 50%.

Some of these figures will have changed due to potentially outdated braking distances and improvements in pedestrian safety, but it's still relevant. 10moh slower will make all the difference, whether you hit someone at speed, or whether you have time to slow down.

According to a BBC program from the 2010, if you hit someone at 30mph there's only a 27% chance they will live. Does this mean cars have become more deadly to pedestrians or do they just invent statistics?

You need to run a filtered lid on those thin filters. Freiburger has a really good series called engine masters and they tested this.They also found out putting a salad bowl on top of the carburetor like a velocity stack increase horsepower.

The problems on that Cobra came as no surprise. I took one look at that thin filter on an engine that size and figured it would be a problem. Gearheads have known that for about 50 years. On the bright side, you just proved just how much of a difference it can make. Good info even if not new. There are lots of people out there that don't know this stuff. The price of a taller filter element is a lot less than most speed parts.

The filters with the top entry added always look a good idea, the main thing I have found that makes the biggest difference especially in a street car with a large engine in a restricted space is a good supply of cool air so ducting into the filter is best choice.

Trick I use for figuring out clearances for under hood stuff is to use Playdough.  I steal a can of it from the kiddo and build a narrow cylinder or pyramid then close the hood and it is soft enough to deform without causing damage to anything. The correct term for air is a fluid. A fluid describes gasses and liquids. You are probably getting turbulent flow at the inlet where the air has to turn which is causing some weird swirling and a bit of pressure drop. I believe this pressure drop will also be related to air velocity. So the higher the velocity the more turbulent the inlet becomes and therefore the more pressure drop at higher RPMs. Since it is naturally aspirated the engine relies on atmospheric pressure to push air and fuel in to the cylinders during the intake stroke. If you have pressure drop at the inlet less air will be able to enter the engine making it run rich. That is my guess. I am not an engineer, but I design downhole tools and deal with turbulent/laminar flow frequently. Pretty neat stuff that most people don‚Äôt really get to see in their everyday lives.

Back in 1969, Porsche created the 917. To save weight, it had an ALUMINUM tubular space-frame!  Pretty sure your frame is 4130 chrome-moly tube.  Anyway, the Porsche frame was prone to cracking, being of an aluminum alloy,  so they drilled little holes where members were welded together, making the inside of the tubes all interconnected.  Then they added a tire-valve so the frame could be pressurized with air, and a small pressure gauge.  If the pressure dropped, that indicated there was a crack that needed to be repaired.  So, I thought that would be a great feature on a dragster chassis... you could even use argon instead of air to ensure the inside doesn't corrode.  A glance at the gauge would tell you if there are any cracks after a particularly bouncy run, and a gas-leak detector could find any crack right away!  Has anyone thought to do that?
It's obvious Rick is all in. Let's see if less frame flex can buy them those thousands that they were losing by this past mid season. Good luck, can't wait to see the color scheme on the new car.

Sales were down for this model year. Mostly because of Ford being the use strike target. Also, the 68 cords were a "build split" year. That means that they made early and late versions. Extra instrument panel got more padding on later versions. The XL package has the greatest differences between early and late versions because the floor console and bucket seats became a separate option for the XL coupes and convertibles. Amazing car, Adam.    I think you have a very early production 1968 car.   I say this because my Dad ordered a 1968 Ford Torino GT fastback and it was built in 1967 before the start of the new year.  It did not have head rests on the bucket seats.   These were low back buckets which during the rest of the 1968 model year had head rests added to comply with Federal Safety regulations.    Just a thought.    Once again you 'rescue' a car that many would not give a second thought and would have been abused as a 'beater' car.    You will give it the respect it deserves and that is a wonderful car for your collection!

I have this CD. It's great. Bob Dylan's Nashville phase with John Wesley Harding is a really profound era in his music. It's more sparse lyrically, and instrumentally, and his singing is becoming more like crooning. From there, he would go into an incredible country music phase with Nashville Skyline, and Self Portrait. His crooning voice remained for those two albums. Bob Dylan is definitely hard to match, when it comes to songwriting. You cannot get any better than that, in modern music. There is a small number of other artists who come close, one being Leonard Cohen, but Bob Dylan is still in a league of his own. Cheers to all the fans of Bob Dylan, from around the world! ‚úåÔ∏è

I think the reason this song always connected so much for everyone is that everyone has this sort of universal experience. Everyone has that first adult relationship, generally  between 18 and 22, that we think is just the be all and end all of our lives. It's different from your high school crushes and relationships. We jump in fully uninhibited because  we were still young and naive enough to believe in fairytale happy endings and that love is going to be easy and it's never going to hurt and you see your whole future in that person...just for it to inevitably come crashing down. And when it's happening at that age, with everything still brand new to you, it feels like you are the only person on the planet who has ever felt that strongly before, no one can possibly understand your devastation...it feels like the entire universe has lied to you somehow. And it DOES change you forever, in positive and negative ways.

Everyone has that one person they think of when they hear this song, and it makes all your personal memories with them come flooding back. And THAT is why I truly believe this is one of the greatest songs ever written. I feel like there aren't that many songs out there that can perfectly capture such a universal experience so perfectly and personally.

Allison Young is fantastic in everything she does, but there is some special magic when she collaborates with Josh Turner. I just love it.

So I‚Äôm listening to this thinking ‚Äúwow, what an amazing song! How come I haven‚Äôt heard that before?‚Äù and then it turns out that‚Äôs because it‚Äôs an original of Allison! Was gonna say that I love your version of the song, but now it needs to be said that not only the arrangement, performance, solos and screenplay are top notch, but the song itself is just super cool and classy!:) Thank you for sharing this!

I didn't think it was possible for Allison's voice to get any better, but I'm hearing some delightful strength and control that wasn't there in years past.  She literally sounds like one of the greats of the silver screen era, a vocalist whom studios back in the day would fight over.  And loved the outtro.  I thought this would be the scene with the tree where Josh dropped the hubcap full of lug nuts and yelled 'Fudge!'   :)
Allison has truly found her voice. Everything about this song is simply magical!  This needs to become a Christmas classic.

Blown away by the voice. This is from a different era. Today female singers sound like wounded animals, but Allison sounds dreamy, warm and strong. I hear Ella, Patsy, Rita Hayworth, the goddesses I missed because I wasn‚Äôt born yet. ‚ù§
Holy shit. Y‚Äôall are making some of the most vital American music of our generation. Endless respect.

When this came to my inbox, I couldn't wait to play it - surely it's a 40s song that I somehow never heard before - then I saw that Alison actually wrote it - well done, you've written a new Christmas classic - and I echo the other comments that Alison, your voice is maturing and developing in a way that amazes me - and Josh, your jazz guitar skills are now up with the greats like Barney Kessel.  Kudos also for your choice of bass and drummer - oh and one final comment, nice solos all round.  You four have really cheered up this 70yo ex guitar player today.   Cheers from the UK.
This is just wonderful!  The arrangement is fantastic and Allison does an absolutely beautiful job on the vocal.  I'm so glad she didn't over sing this.  Her tone and control were perfect.

How is it possible for Allison's voice to get ever better? She's got a rich, resonant contralto in this song I've never heard in her before. And Josh is a master of any musical genre (as is Allison) with his creative, melodic soloing. Of course, he's a great singer as well.
But among their talents, one is often overlooked during the glowing comments on their videos. Both of them are fabulous songwriters. This song and the songs on their EP is ample proof of that.
Allison, Josh, and their community of artists produce the consistently best and most uplifting content anywhere. Thank you so much for this beautiful piece!
Absolutely amazing! The crews that Josh assembles are great. This is how music is supposed to be‚Ä¶.

Shout to Josh fabulous as always.  Special shout out to the bass player, I could actually hear you and it was really nice.  Now that drummer, he is so creative with the unconventional use of the cymbals!  It was all so delightful!
That Oktava ML-219 microphone and Allison's voice is pure magic! Excellent well-written song.... I love it!
Love this! - what a duo
If you put Allison on stage singing in a black & white film starring Fred Astaire & Ginger Rogers I would never know that she was from 2022. Timeless.
I could listen to her sing all day long!

Whoa, this was a surprise. This was part of that cool Electronica sound in the 90s where people meshed different genres with electronic dance music. Something I think you'd both like for different reasons is the group Portishead. They feature a very distinct female vocalist and fall under the 90's Electronica umbrella but more towards Trip-Hop. What's trip-hop? It's a cool blend of hip hop beats with electronic pop, sometimes elements of jazz and is real atmospheric and moody stuff, but so cool. I'd recommend Portishead's "Roads", "Glory Box", "Strangers", Only You or Numb.

I remember a few months before Republica's debut single, their record label sent out what was known as a cassette single to all the people on their mailing list. This cassingle  had about 90 second samples of four different Republica songs and you had to tick a box on the included postcard which track was your favourite and mail it back to the label. Months later and Ready To Go was the winner. It came out as a single followed by a remix which fared even better in the charts. 90s market research pre - internet!!

‚ÄîPlenty of people have accusatory, unfavorable stuff to say regarding the simplicity of (and, also: notable similarity of plenty of) the songs on this album ...however: if that is what they think, they, obviously, weren't alive, or listening to music, at the time (or, simply: aren't paying attention!), because:the entire music industry was "dumbing-it-down" and (simultaneously) trying to "amalgamate": "Punk rock" and "catchy pop" and synths and loud, crunchy guitars [which were the identifiable things that seemed to be present in most of the music that attracted larger audiences (in the late '80s and, then, early, '90s), although the label heads couldn't, actually, figure out "why."]
Most bands (and often: constructed ones) did so BADLY!

Republica, just, hits on all cylinders and, their writing and arrangements are what make them stand out (among a laundry-list of also-rans, not worthy of any attention, at all).
The album is undeniable. (even the follow-up was quite good!) and as a song-writer, there are little (important) nuances you will notice, if you are listening.
The "everyday fan" (who pays attn. to NONE of that [nor understands HOW to!]), will  (more-than-likely) NOT notice, but: they will, still, find it impossible to: keep their booty and/or legs from movin'!

This is, definitely, a "synth-driven" band ...a common feature in "alterna-" whatever styles of the '90s (post '94, particularly). ...but: what it had done was: it took the stereotyped ''80s synth-pop" sound and attitude, and "darkened it."  ...A lot more "heft."...heaviness, density and, also: cynicism, darkness, mocking,...in the lyrics (even if they were funny).
Republica, definitely, features buzzy-guitars (with a clean (processed) edge) and throbbing, club-beat (synth-)bass and beats, but they have catchy, quirky, memorable melodies and an overall celebratory attitude.
If you can't have fun to THIS, you can't have fun AT ALL.

REPUBLICA were a cool-ass band (and just, personally: some of the loveliest, kindest, most fun and convivial people I've ever met.
They made being in their presence a joy.  They made the slog of touring an excellent experience (you don't ALWAYS get that!)‚Äîand EVERY night, WITHOUT fail: they brought the audience a SUPERB, undeniable show & an easy, great time.).

You should make time to watch the 1996 film "Grace of My Heart." The main character, played by Illiana Douglas, is loosely based on Carole King and her life in music. Not exactly a biopic, but brilliantly conceived as a trip through the musical world of the late 50s through the early 70s through the eyes of a woman who is one of the most prolific songwriters of her generation, writing hit after hit for all of the great acts of the time, until she gets the opportunity to write and perform one of the great albums of all time.

"Go Away Little Girl," 
"I'm Into Something Good," 
"Take Good Care of My Baby," 
"Up on the Roof,"

I am soon 34 years old, I never had the chance to see Pantera live in person as I was a shit kid in the 90's growing up in a small fishing village in Northern Norway, with no possibility to go see them. Obviously it would have been amazing if Vinnie Paul and Dimebag were still alive, and they could have been reunited. But that dream was broken in 2004, and our hearts have been forever broken since that time. Seeing and hearing Pantera live has been a dream of mine since I was a kid, it was my favorite metal band growing up. I still have fond memories of blasting Vulgar Display of Power and The Great Southern Trendkill for the first time. Those records were so heavy, it made a lasting inpact on me. Heck I even loved Reinventing the Steel, and still consider it to be an underated record. Now Rex and Phil are back, with the best friends of the brothers and the band handling the drum and guitar duties. Zakk and Charlie are doing an amazing job, it sounds heavy, energetic and inspiring! Phil sounds fantastic; truly putting is heart and soul into every note, as well as Rex, who locks in perfectly with Charlie as the backbone of the rhythm section. This just brings me back into my boyhood room, back with my heroes playing on my tired cdplayer.

The music lives on and the dream of hearing this music live, lives on. This is truly for the fans OF THE MUSIC. That's why this is happening. I can't speak for Dime or Vinnie at all, as other people have been trying to do, and rather negatively through their channels stating "they are turning in their graves!"...or "Dime is ashamed", and even calling it a fiasco. It's both disrespectful to the music, the legacy of Pantera; Phil, Rex, Zakk and Charlie, the Abbott-brothers and their families, who gave their blessings for this to happen. Haters;  If you absolutely need to hate, then go do it somewhere else, this isn't about you or your opinions. This is about the music of Pantera, true legacy. And we are blessed to finally hear it again in live format. And I would like to think, that this is what Vinnie and Dime always wanted.

I encourage anyone who feels like they have writers block to open their mind to the possibility that they are writing music from a place of habituation that has run its course. From my experience, most people pull from a set of characteristics that they are used to, and usually they are a mix of whatever their favorite bands do. Strumming patterns. Drum beats. Guitar or keyboard sounds. Secondly, they believe that any preplanning or preselecting or acknowledgement of musical elements is "unnatural" or "not from the heart". But those are illusions. I suggest to people who are stuck and have writers block the following tips.

1. Melody rhythm, NOT the pitches, are the soul of your melody. Work on your melody rhythms by realizing they can only occur at 3 possible points: before, on, or after beat one of your measure. Take your favorite 25 songs (that have been most widely loved by more than yourself) and list on paper where the melody rhythms start and stop. This will make placement of your melody rhythms a more conscious decision. Not relying on habit, and having to choose from the only 3 possible starting points, breaks writers block.

2. Create a list of words and phrases that stand out and have alot of impact when you hear them. Not words like "distinguish" or "good" etc. You want punchy evocative words like "haunted" or "xerox" or "broken". Go through all your favorite songs and movies. Make lists of every emotionally impactful phrase or word that you personally like. Refer to these lists when you are writing lyrics. Remember, verbs are the secret to strong lyrics. Just like melody rhythm is the soul of melody, verbs are the soul of your lyric. Using these emotional word lists break writers block.

3. Create low points. When you write a chord progression. Be aware of what constitutes a full close, a half close, or something continuing. These are called "cadences". Almost all new writers who finally figure out how to write a close or half close immediately off to the races using that trick over and over because it is the only trick they have, But the experienced writer knows to create low points so that the high points seem higher. So try looking at your favorite songs across all genres at where they place half closes and full closes and you will see that many great hooks and songs are a series of half closes followed by a full, or vice versa. Anything you write that you feel proud of, be it a lick, or a chord change, ask yourself how can i write a slightly less "final" sounding version of this, and place it appropriately so that you arent just leaning on that one trick you finally figured out. Dont just "give". Learn to withhold, then give. Creating variants of your riffs or melodies breaks writers block.

4. Understand melody speed vs harmony (the underlying chords) speed. Melody can only move at 3 speeds. Slower than the harmony, faster than the harmony, and at the same speed as the harmony. Listen to your favorite popular hit songs and determine where the melody moves faster than the chords behind it, and where it changes to one of the other options etc. You will find things like, the melody moves slower for the verse, then faster in the chorus etc. There is great power in alot of 80s hits in having the melody move in time with the harmony for just a moment or two. Becoming familiar with how your favorite songs use these tricks, and then applying them to your own works to breathe life into them breaks writers block.

There are many more of these tricks and techniques hidden in plain sight that nobody ever talks about or helps you figure out. But start with these few and your writing will improve beyond what you ever thought you could write. Force yourself to face these little challenges that at first seem like chores, and unnatural, and soon they become habit and you apply them without thinking, only feeling. People say "I dont want to overthink music" so I refuse tricks like this. But, you are already selecting these elements of your compositions by habit anyways. You are already choosing all these elements, just not with intent and familiarity. So get familiar. The sooner you get familiar, the less it will be a chore, and the more you will start to truly see how talented you really are.

I still dinked around with music during those times but my daughter has graduated from college (masters in Accounting - yes, I'm proud of her) and my son is a senior in college (majoring in Animation and business - also very proud of him).  I've had more time over the past few years to focus more on music (I need to record and produce more) - mostly guitar playing but a little writing and recording.  

I was really touched when my family went around the table for my birthday and they each listed things they love most about me (we do that for everyone's birthdays).  My daughter and son both said that they loved that I still work/practice the guitar and write music to "keep the dream alive."  They said it gives them hope and enjoyment.  My wife is also SUPER supportive of my love and expensive habit.  That validated everything for me - the support I give to them continuously as a father is being reciprocated (I never doubted it) and that it's ok to take some time for your self doing things you love (good, constructive things, that is).

It's now 7  years later my kids are grown up and not living at home anymore.  I have the time and space to be more active in music and I really enjoy it.  The music was always in me. Honesty! This is why this channel is my favorite. My gf of 7 year just left me. As a bargaining chip I told my gf....."if i give up music completely will you stay?"  That didn't matter much to her either way. She was dead set on leaving. One of the most encouraging things I ever read many years ago was a magazine article, interview with Brian May of Queen. He said that there were many times when he would not pick up a guitar for 3-6 months because of this phenomenon you are talking about. I thought to myself, wow, I couldn‚Äôt imagine this guy going a day without playing. But how liberating it was to see someone of that magnitude being OK with walking away at times. I‚Äôm telling the story because that‚Äôs how much impact it had on me and that‚Äôs going back probably 25 years ago. Thank you, Barry, because even in this, it‚Äôs very inspiring and liberating. At the end of the day, musicians are more than just creators.

I enjoy playing music most of the time, and get tired of it others. I have the caveat of having a job in another industry, leaving music as more of a hobby for me. It is useful to have a job and a hobby to bounce back and forth to and from, because like you said sometimes the creativity for music ebbs and flows. I think if people find some other hobby to distract the brain from music, it will be easier to start fresh when they get back into your studio. Likewise I enjoy my job, but sometimes it wears on me and I go to my hobbies to distract myself until I feel more motivated for creativity concerning my job. The hobbies I choose have no business element to them, as that adds the stress of timelines and demand I have in other parts of my life.

I've been saving up a recording setup for at least 8 years now. Bought one drum at a time. One microphone at a time.  Zzounds was my best friend, got an analog synth, and, how I found your channel, an Apollo x8p, bot took me a year to pay off each. A ll of it is studio grade premium equipment. I've never heard any of it. Most of it just collects dust.

Thunderbolt 3 was insanely expensive when I got the Apollo, never could get financing. And now it's yesteryear's tech. And magically right when I finally had things going right, I got hit with some gnarly rootkit/ virus/hacker something or rather, killed 2 macs and 3 PCs. Trying to save my kid's baby pictures from corruption, recovering fragments that reinfect whatever I put them on. All of them had an issue, in one form or another, all the way down to the root.  

Not unlike a lot of us creative types.  The curse of needing to create, the blessing of a passion understood by few. I've gone from only knowing how to run Ableton to being totally comfortable in terminal on Linux/Mac and Windows. Their higher level semi hollows use a JB/Jazz combo, so it's not surprising that they're using a similar approach here.
