Many years ago birds built a nest on a beam under our roof. One day we found a baby bird (eyes closed, no feathers) on the ground below the nest. The mother was circling around him. Immediately we put him back in the nest. A couple days later he or one of the other babies was on the ground again and we put the baby back in the nest. A few days later one of the poor babies was stuck and dangling upsidedown from the nest. We carefully unhooked him and put him back. None of us could handle finding more babies on the ground or dangling. It was a miracle that none of them died to begin with.  So we made a second nest and put it in a box and nailed the box right next to the original nest. The box was enclosed except one side which was fully open to the nest and another side was cut just low enough for the parents to fly into. No more babies on the ground or dangling after that! And they used the second nest. The popular spot and our makeshift box nest was used for years. All happy, beautiful birds!

I think the misconception about mama birds "not coming back" is because they can't physically get the baby back into the nest and so people assumed the mama is abandoning it. In reality, they just physically can't do anything for their baby to get them back into the nest. Once a baby has fallen from the nest, only a human or other animal could get the baby back inside, and if you can't, and the bird can't, then the baby has to adapt. I've seen babies stuck on the ground where I'd get them under a rose bush for protection, and the parents would perch near the rose bush. They couldn't do anything much, but they could perch, watch, and potentially bring food to the baby. But if people don't watch for that behavior, they were just like "oh I guess it was abandoned". It's good that you kept bringing it outside because that gives the parent birds a chance to see that the baby is still in the area, even if they can't reach it. It's too bad you couldn't reach the nest. I have a tree in my yard that had some matted old branches that formed a sort of "cubby hole" in the leaves of the tree. Usually if a baby bird fell, I would stick it into that cubby, it was dark like a nest or cave and the baby would run back into the back of it, where cats wouldn't get it at least. And usually I would see adults hanging out in the tree next to it like they were watching, so I hope that I helped them by putting the baby in a spot where the parents could reach it still. Also had a baby hawk fall from its nest too early and the parents were flying over nad perching on wires, all they could do was watch him and hope he'd learn to fly soon. Sadly he had heatstroke and some smoke inhalation from nearby fires, which is probably why he jumped from the nest early out of desperation. We took him to a wildlife center for rescue but they called and said he died, he was just too sick, the poor thing. But even after that the parents flew around for a while, looking for him :( so they definitely don't abandon them, I'm glad more people are correcting that myth.

JOEY PLEASE READ!!!! If you allow the mom to wean them on her own, she won't have to deal with engorged nipples. That is not good for mom!!!! She will slowly let the pups nurse less and less. And you, feed them food. Which means they nurse less and less. And mom will regurgitate food for the pups, which is the NATURAL WAY!!! And their tummies can handle the new introduction to solid foods a lot better. It is the natural way of things. It helps pups and helps mom. And, they get disciplined by mom in the process. Which makes for a much better dog. Having human interaction is important. And learning how to interact with another dog, through moms discipline, helps them learn as well. PLEASE DO IT THIS WAY FROM NOW ON!! PLEASE! Mom and pups benefit so much from the natural process. And, makes it easier for you, because  she will attend to them a bit longer.

i watched more than one video regarding dogtraining. the main difference i noticed: other trainers dont allow the dogs to get attached. its business only. and sometimes i saw trainers who educated the dogs by istalling fear of punishment.

Notice Luke's calm demeanor ... even when confronted with common myths .... when a dog sizes you up they see that (and all dogs will size you up, it;s a survival instinct) ... I've trained large, powerful herding/guard dogs all my life (Bouvier des Flandres) and there are great difference in breed personalities/behaviors ... and I agree with Luke, the early years 8 mo's to 2 years old are critical in "socializing" (a broad term) to both people and other dogs .... the best advice I ever got was from my Grandfather who's family bred champion working Border Collies for over a decade ... he told me to learn to think more like a dog and less like a person ... to see the world from their perspective (as Luke says "reading the dog" ) ... I'm down to just one Bouv at 67 ... an intact 8 year old male, sweet boy with me and friends he knows (was raised with a laid back female Spinone) ... but he's never been good with other dogs ... he's edgy around them and it sets off other dogs easily ... he is what we call Belgians call an "On Guarde" dog ... part of the breed characteristics ... luckily he's well trained and easy to control for me ... but would be considered a "problem dog" for most, or not familiar with the breed ...

Two suggestions from a lifelong cat person. I've noticed you call dogs by their names but generally call all the cats "cat" or "kitty." Actually, cats often DO respond to their names, even if they are not as obedient as dogs LOL. It might help to use their names! Also, I've had a cat professionally groomed using a high velocity dryer like yours, and it really scared her, which worried me. When that same kitty got very old, I began regularly bathing her myself. What I found is that using first a soft, warm towel, and then a regular hair dryer on low velocity worked great. I turned the heat to a higher setting and she LOVED that, while less noise and lower "blowing" kept her from being scared. Sometimes I'd gently brush her while I used the hair dryer. It took a few minutes longer but worked out much better. She even began to welcome getting bathed and dried.

Today I will be grooming a black domestic shorthair cat. This cat was recently hit by a car, and resurrected by being placed in an ancient burial ground.

The owners have asked me to use my strongest shampoo, as they have tried bathing him, but can't seem to get the smell of sour earth out of his fur.

This cat was very lethargic during his bath. At times, it felt like I was washing a piece of meat. As you can see here, his eyes sometimes glow. This is one of the byproducts of being resurrected in a burial ground.

Crossing an ancient barrier to resurrect a recently deceased pet is something I cannot recommend. It tends to not end well for you or your loved ones, and with animal shelters receiving countless unwanted animals every day, I would recommend adoption instead.

Years ago I had a neighbor, that got chicks for his daughters, every easter, and without fail every year the chicks turned out to be roosters, this drove my father ( who had been raised on an Iowa poultry farm) right straight up the wall, with their constant crowing, they were kept in a makeshift pen, under the neighbors back porch, from which they were constantly escaping, until finally one day I came home from school, to find dad, standing in the yard, a can of beer in hand, watching said roosters, scratching up moms garden, without taking his eyes off the birds dad prefaced our conversation, ( which would usually have been to tell me I was the one cooking dinner that night) with " do you still have that long handled fish net? ( our town was on Lake Michigan, and I spent a lot of my time fishing the civic pier, thus I kept the net to deal with my larger catches) when I replied that of course I did, he told me good go get it, I did dad then handed me a twenty, and said go to the store, ( a block away) and get some flour, eggs, and a box of cornflake crumbs, get yourself a snack while you're at it and take your time! So when I got home about 45 minutes later, ( my Brother was at the store too, and I decided to share dad's largess) there on the drain board,  were two freshly dressed, and cut up chickens! Dad dipped them in egg dusted them with flour, and rolled them in the cornflake crumbs, and set them to bake while I made some mashed potatoes, mixed vegetables, and biscuits, by the time mom got home dinner was ready, while we were eating mom asked dad, where he had found such fresh chicken! I started to snicker, but dad gave me a swift kick under the table, and that look, that meant I had better keep my mouth shut! The next afternoon, the neighbor was out in his yard, and he asked me if I had seen his darn chickens, I was tempted to say yeah, and they were delicious, but ( not wanting to get called a chicken thief) I held my tongue, and simply replied nope! That was the last year he got them, as his eldest daughter went into a convent, and his youngest entered High School and was no longer interested in caring for chickens.

And a tip for the less patient (like those with ADHD/EFDD), find a 30 minute podcast or something to listen to while you do it if you fear you may grow restless during the feeding process. Never try to speed it up to finish quicker.

The Kitty Kollars were a godsend when our young cat had an e-tube placed in an emergency.  The alternative is a high level of skill with nonstick bandages and adhesive wrap, which all has to be redone every time you feed. We used two of the "kollars" so one could be washed while the other was in use- super easy.  Our young cat figured out in 3 feedings that, when we sat down together in the particular feeding spot and went through all this wackiness with the syringes, suddenly his hunger would go away!  

His feeding tube was much longer than Chouchou's, which wasn't good. He broke the "Christmas tree" attachment twice (shattered the plastic) by whacking it on the floor. The second time, he also tore out all of the stitches securing the tube to his neck, which was a real problem since he did this on the first day of the 2021 winter storm in Texas.  Huge shout-out to the emergency vet techs who helped us despite no power, no water, half staff, snow everywhere.  

Also, you would not believe the mess created when you try to get an air bubble out of the food syringe while pointing the tip UP at the ceiling. Good grief.

I think this may need some explaining. In the UK, there are two hare species, blue hares, also known as mountain hares and brown hares. You can hunt blue hares in the UK legally. However, you can only hunt blue hares with birds of prey or a gun, not a dog. Hunting with dogs in the UK is semi-illegal, but some animals, such as rabbits and foxes, can be hunted with up to two dogs. Packs of dogs cannot be used, unless you are ratting. So basically hare coursing is illegal, but technically under the hunting with dogs act, isn't illegal. Basically, they never really out right banned it.
Edit:
The reason I know the law is because A-I do a lot of conservation work. B- I do pest control and the removal of invasive species. I often use dogs, ferrets and even birds of prey to aid me in this-usually I hunt rabbits, grey squirrels, american mink, brown rats etc. Not foxes though or anything like that! However, hare occasionally do get chased by dogs or hawks and it can be very hard to prove whether or not it was an accident or intentional. I know the law as a means of explaining anything that could happen, were we to have an accident or if a working animal misidentifies quarry and goes after the wrong animal. I mean hares no harm.

Edit 2:
Here is something else. If you would like to hunt with a dog please get landowner permission first! Too many farmers are waking up to find people hunting on their land. Farmers do not mind if you want to remove agricultural pests such as rabbits, brown rats etc but please get written permission first. You can scare livestock, damage crops and negatively affect the farmer's livelihood. Please don't do this, respect the countryside and the people whose earnings rely on it.
